{"title_page": "French Gigs", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name        = French Gigs \n| type        = live\n| artist      = [[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]]\n| cover       = Frith&Coxhill AlbumCover FrenchGigs.jpg\n| released    = {{Start date|1983}}\n| recorded    = {{flatlist|\n*1978\n*1981\n}}\n| venue       = {{unbulleted list\n|\u2022 Musiques de Traverses festival, Maison de la Culture Andr\u00e9 Malraux, [[Reims]], France\n|\u2022 M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, [[Limoges]], France\n|\u2022 Sainte Croix auditorium, [[Poitiers]], France\n}}\n| genre       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Experimental music]]\n*[[free improvisation]]\n}}\n| length      = {{Duration|m=48|s=32}}\n| label       = AAA (France)\n| producer    =\n}}\n\n'''''French Gigs''''' is a 1983 live collaborative album of [[Musical improvisation|improvised]] [[experimental music]] by [[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]]. It was recorded live in France in [[Limoges]] and [[Poitiers]] in October 1978, and in [[Reims]] in 1981. The album was released on LP by AAA in 1983,<ref name=Discogs-LP/> and on CD by AYAA in 1991.<ref name=Discogs-CD/> The CD release includes an extra track recorded via correspondence in 1991\u201392 by Coxhill in London and Frith in [[Munich]].<ref name=Discogs-CD/><ref name=LinerNotes-CD/>\n\n==Background==\n[[Fred Frith]] began playing with [[Lol Coxhill]] in the early 1970s, which introduced Frith to the London improvised music scene.<ref name=Breznikar/> Coxhill went on to perform as a guest with [[Henry Cow]], a group Frith was a member of at the time, on several occasions between 1972 and 1977.<ref name=HC-chron-calyx/> In 1974 Frith also played with Coxhill in [[Welfare State International|Welfare State]], a British performance art group.<ref name=Patterson/> Bill Smith and Dan Lander stated in their book ''Music Is Rapid Transportation'' that Coxhill's improvisation technique had a \"lasting impact\" on Frith.{{sfn|Smith|Lander|2010|p=105}}\n\nIn October 1978, shortly after Henry Cow split up in August that year, Frith and Coxhill undertook a short tour in France, playing in [[Limoges]] and [[Poitiers]]. Several years later in 1981, they participated in an unscheduled performance at a concert in [[Reims]]. The material on ''French Gigs'' was taken from the 1978 tour and the 1981 concert.<ref name=Chadbourne/><ref name=LinerNotes-LP/>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=Chadbourne/>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''\n| rev2Score = Favorable<ref name=Scott/>\n}}\nIn a review of the LP release of ''French Gigs'' at [[AllMusic]], [[Eugene Chadbourne]] compared the [[musical tone|tone]] of Coxhill's soprano saxophone to that of [[Sidney Bechet]], but added that Coxhill often explores contexts beyond that of traditional jazz. Chadbourne said Frith's tabletop guitars add \"a magnificent sort of orchestral accompaniment\" to Coxhill, and praised Frith's production for avoiding the trap of reducing the collection to \"meaningless highlights\".<ref name=Chadbourne/> Chadbourne looked forward to a CD release of the album where he hoped that additional material would be added.<ref name=Chadbourne/>\n\nReviewing the album in ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]'', Richard Scott said Coxhill and Frith cover a wide range of musical styles, making generic categorisation impossible. He described the recording as \"sometimes expansive, beautiful, lush, sometimes dry, scratchy and obscure\".<ref name=Scott/> He said the duo \"pace around each other, provide contexts for each other, listen and respond in ways that rarely amount to any particular style or approach.\" Coxhill's saxophone at times sounds like bagpipes, and Frith's guitar like an orchestra, and \"[a]s such there is not a lot to go on, and no particular reason why it should work as well as it does\".<ref name=Scott/> Scott concluded: \"It's great: one of the few recordings of improvisation that continues to beguile and seduce after several listens.\"<ref name=Scott/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by [[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]].\n\n===LP release===\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Side A\n| extra_column = Venue / date\n| title_width = 15em\n| extra_width = 45em\n| title1 = Reims\n| extra1 = Musiques de Traverses festival, Maison de la Culture Andr\u00e9 Malraux, [[Reims]], France / 1981\n| length1 = 25:59\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Side B\n| extra_column = Venue / date\n| title_width = 15em\n| extra_width = 45em\n| title1 = Limoges 1\n| extra1 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, [[Limoges]], France / 26 October 1978\n| length1 = 9:13\n| title2 = Poitiers\n| extra2 = Sainte Croix auditorium, [[Poitiers]], France / 25 October 1978\n| length2 = 9:52\n| title3 = Limoges 2\n| extra3 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, Limoges, France / 26 October 1978\n| length3 = 3:28\n}}\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-LP/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-LP/>\n\n===CD release===\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column = Venue / date\n| title_width = 15em\n| extra_width = 45em\n| title1 = Reims\n| extra1 = Musiques de Traverses festival, Maison de la Culture Andr\u00e9 Malraux, Reims, France / 1981\n| length1 = 25:59\n| title2 = Limoges 1\n| extra2 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, Limoges, France / 26 October 1978\n| length2 = 9:13\n| title3 = Poitiers\n| extra3 = Sainte Croix auditorium, Poitiers, France / 25 October 1978\n| length3 = 9:52\n| title4 = Limoges 2\n| extra4 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, Limoges, France / 26 October 1978\n| length4 = 3:28\n| title5 = M\u00fcnchen/London\n| extra5 = London (Coxhill) and [[Munich]] (Frith) / 1991\u201392\n| length5 = 11:38\n}}\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-CD/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-CD/>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Lol Coxhill]] \u2013 soprano saxophone\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-LP/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-LP/>\n\n===Sound and artwork===\n*LP\n**Track A1 \u2013 recorded by Dominique Diebold\n**Tracks B1, B3 \u2013 recorded by Jean Claude \"James\" Dupron; edited and mixed by Fred Frith\n**Track B2 \u2013 recorded by Michel Demily; edited and mixed by Fred Frith\n*CD\n**Tracks A1, B1\u2013B3 \u2013 as for the LP\n**Track 5 \u2013 soprano saxophone recorded by Lol Coxhill; guitar recorded by Benedykt Grodon; mixed by Jean-Maurice Rossel\n*Design \u2013 Beno\u00eet Proust, William Th\u00e9ry\n*Photography \u2013 Lol Coxhill by Philippe Taillefer; Fred Frith by G\u00e9rard Richard\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-LP/><ref name=LinerNotes-CD/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-LP/><ref name=Discogs-CD/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=Chadbourne>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/french-gigs-mw0000838510 |title=French Gigs |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=HC-chron-calyx>{{cite web |url=http://www.calyx-canterbury.fr/bands/chrono/henrycow.html|title=Henry Cow Chronology |website=Calyx: The Canterbury Website |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Breznikar>{{cite magazine |last=Breznikar |first=Klemen |url=https://www.psychedelicbabymag.com/2012/01/fred-frith-interview-about-henry-cow.html |title=Fred Frith interview about Henry Cow & beyond |magazine=It\u2019s Psychedelic Baby |date=6 January 2012 |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Patterson>{{cite web |last=Patterson |first=Archie |url=https://medium.com/@archiepatterson/art-is-not-a-mirror-it-is-a-hammer-john-grierson-f9e569cdfa6e |title='Art is not a mirror, it is a hammer.' ~John Grierson |website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Discogs-LP>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Lol-Coxhill-And-Fred-Frith-French-Gigs/release/1249517 |title=Lol Coxhill And Fred Frith \u2013 French Gigs |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Discogs-CD>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Lol-Coxhill-Fred-Frith-French-Gigs/release/667331 |title=Lol Coxhill & Fred Frith \u2013 French Gigs |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=LinerNotes-LP>{{cite AV media notes |title=French Gigs |others=[[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]] |year=1983 |last=AAA |type=LP liner notes}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=LinerNotes-CD>{{cite AV media notes |title=French Gigs |others=[[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]] |year=1991 |last=AYAA |type=CD liner notes}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Scott>{{cite magazine |last=Scott |first=Richard |date=June 1993 |title=Lol Coxhill et Fred Frith: ''French Gigs'' |magazine=[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]] |publisher= |publication-place= |issue=112 |pages=56-57 |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn=0952-0686 |oclc= }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Bill |last2=Lander |first2=Dan |title=Music Is Rapid Transportation: ... From the Beatles to Xenakis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fv3j4DHm0bwC |year=2010 |publisher=Charivari Press |isbn=978-1-895166-04-0 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Fred Frith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French Gigs}}\n[[Category:1983 live albums]]\n[[Category:Collaborative albums]]\n[[Category:Experimental music albums]]\n[[Category:Free improvisation albums]]\n[[Category:Fred Frith live albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name        = French Gigs \n| type        = live\n| artist      = [[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]]\n| cover       = Frith&Coxhill AlbumCover FrenchGigs.jpg\n| released    = {{Start date|1983}}\n| recorded    = {{flatlist|\n*1978\n*1981\n}}\n| venue       = {{unbulleted list\n|\u2022 Musiques de Traverses festival, Maison de la Culture Andr\u00e9 Malraux, [[Reims]], France\n|\u2022 M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, [[Limoges]], France\n|\u2022 Sainte Croix auditorium, [[Poitiers]], France\n}}\n| genre       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Experimental music]]\n*[[free improvisation]]\n}}\n| length      = {{Duration|m=48|s=32}}\n| label       = AAA (France)\n| producer    =\n}}\n\n'''''French Gigs''''' is a 1983 live collaborative album of [[Musical improvisation|improvised]] [[experimental music]] by [[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]]. It was recorded live in France in [[Limoges]] and [[Poitiers]] in October 1978, and in [[Reims]] in 1981. The album was released on LP by AAA in 1983,<ref name=Discogs-LP/> and on CD by AYAA in 1991.<ref name=Discogs-CD/> The CD release includes an extra track recorded via correspondence in 1991\u201392 by Coxhill in London and Frith in [[Munich]].<ref name=Discogs-CD/><ref name=LinerNotes-CD/>\n\n==Background==\n[[Fred Frith]] began playing with [[Lol Coxhill]] in the early 1970s, which introduced Frith to the London improvised music scene.<ref name=Breznikar/> Coxhill went on to perform as a guest with [[Henry Cow]], a group Frith was a member of at the time, on several occasions between 1972 and 1977.<ref name=HC-chron-calyx/> In 1974 Frith also played with Coxhill in [[Welfare State International|Welfare State]], a British performance art group.<ref name=Patterson/> Bill Smith and Dan Lander stated in their book ''Music Is Rapid Transportation'' that Coxhill's improvisation technique had a \"lasting impact\" on Frith.{{sfn|Smith|Lander|2010|p=105}}\n\nIn October 1978, shortly after Henry Cow split up in August that year, Frith and Coxhill undertook a short tour in France, playing in [[Limoges]] and [[Poitiers]]. Several years later in 1981, they participated in an unscheduled performance at a concert in [[Reims]]. The material on ''French Gigs'' was taken from the 1978 tour and the 1981 concert.<ref name=Chadbourne/><ref name=LinerNotes-LP/>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=Chadbourne/>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''\n| rev2Score = Favorable<ref name=Scott/>\n}}\nIn a review of the LP release of ''French Gigs'' at [[AllMusic]], [[Eugene Chadbourne]] compared the [[musical tone|tone]] of Coxhill's soprano saxophone to that of [[Sidney Bechet]], but added that Coxhill often explores contexts beyond that of traditional jazz. Chadbourne said Frith's tabletop guitars add \"a magnificent sort of orchestral accompaniment\" to Coxhill, and praised Frith's production for avoiding the trap of reducing the collection to \"meaningless highlights\".<ref name=Chadbourne/> Chadbourne looked forward to a CD release of the album where he hoped that additional material would be added.<ref name=Chadbourne/>\n\nReviewing the album in ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]'', Richard Scott said Coxhill and Frith cover a wide range of musical styles, making generic categorisation impossible. He described the recording as \"sometimes expansive, beautiful, lush, sometimes dry, scratchy and obscure\".<ref name=Scott/> He said the duo \"pace around each other, provide contexts for each other, listen and respond in ways that rarely amount to any particular style or approach.\" Coxhill's saxophone at times sounds like bagpipes, and Frith's guitar like an orchestra, and \"[a]s such there is not a lot to go on, and no particular reason why it should work as well as it does\".<ref name=Scott/> Scott concluded: \"It's great: one of the few recordings of improvisation that continues to beguile and seduce after several listens.\"<ref name=Scott/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks composed by [[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]].\n\n===LP release===\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Side A\n| extra_column = Venue / date\n| title_width = 15em\n| extra_width = 45em\n| title1 = Reims\n| extra1 = Musiques de Traverses festival, Maison de la Culture Andr\u00e9 Malraux, [[Reims]], France / 1981\n| length1 = 25:59\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Side B\n| extra_column = Venue / date\n| title_width = 15em\n| extra_width = 45em\n| title1 = Limoges 1\n| extra1 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, [[Limoges]], France / 26 October 1978\n| length1 = 9:13\n| title2 = Poitiers\n| extra2 = Sainte Croix auditorium, [[Poitiers]], France / 25 October 1978\n| length2 = 9:52\n| title3 = Limoges 2\n| extra3 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, Limoges, France / 26 October 1978\n| length3 = 3:28\n}}\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-LP/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-LP/>\n\n===CD release===\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column = Venue / date\n| title_width = 15em\n| extra_width = 45em\n| title1 = Reims\n| extra1 = Musiques de Traverses festival, Maison de la Culture Andr\u00e9 Malraux, Reims, France / 1981\n| length1 = 25:59\n| title2 = Limoges 1\n| extra2 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, Limoges, France / 26 October 1978\n| length2 = 9:13\n| title3 = Poitiers\n| extra3 = Sainte Croix auditorium, Poitiers, France / 25 October 1978\n| length3 = 9:52\n| title4 = Limoges 2\n| extra4 = M.J.C. Ali\u00e9nor D'Aquitaine, Limoges, France / 26 October 1978\n| length4 = 3:28\n| title5 = M\u00fcnchen/London\n| extra5 = London (Coxhill) and [[Munich]] (Frith) / 1991\u201392\n| length5 = 11:38\n}}\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-CD/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-CD/>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Lol Coxhill]] \u2013 soprano saxophone\n*[[Fred Frith]] \u2013 guitar\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-LP/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-LP/>\n\n===Sound and artwork===\n*LP\n**Track A1 \u2013 recorded by Dominique Diebold\n**Tracks B1, B3 \u2013 recorded by Jean Claude \"James\" Dupron; edited and mixed by Fred Frith\n**Track B2 \u2013 recorded by Michel Demily; edited and mixed by Fred Frith\n*CD\n**Tracks A1, B1\u2013B3 \u2013 as for the LP\n**Track 5 \u2013 soprano saxophone recorded by Lol Coxhill; guitar recorded by Benedykt Grodon; mixed by Jean-Maurice Rossel\n*Design \u2013 Beno\u00eet Proust, William Th\u00e9ry\n*Photography \u2013 Lol Coxhill by Philippe Taillefer; Fred Frith by G\u00e9rard Richard\n\nSources: [[Liner notes]],<ref name=LinerNotes-LP/><ref name=LinerNotes-CD/> [[Discogs]].<ref name=Discogs-LP/><ref name=Discogs-CD/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n*<ref name=Chadbourne>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/french-gigs-mw0000838510 |title=French Gigs |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n*<ref name=HC-chron-calyx>{{cite web |url=http://www.calyx-canterbury.fr/bands/chrono/henrycow.html|title=Henry Cow Chronology |website=Calyx: The Canterbury Website |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n*<ref name=Breznikar>{{cite magazine |last=Breznikar |first=Klemen |url=https://www.psychedelicbabymag.com/2012/01/fred-frith-interview-about-henry-cow.html |title=Fred Frith interview about Henry Cow & beyond |magazine=It\u2019s Psychedelic Baby |date=6 January 2012 |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n*<ref name=Patterson>{{cite web |last=Patterson |first=Archie |url=https://medium.com/@archiepatterson/art-is-not-a-mirror-it-is-a-hammer-john-grierson-f9e569cdfa6e |title='Art is not a mirror, it is a hammer.' ~John Grierson |website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n*<ref name=Discogs-LP>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Lol-Coxhill-And-Fred-Frith-French-Gigs/release/1249517 |title=Lol Coxhill And Fred Frith \u2013 French Gigs |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n*<ref name=Discogs-CD>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Lol-Coxhill-Fred-Frith-French-Gigs/release/667331 |title=Lol Coxhill & Fred Frith \u2013 French Gigs |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n*<ref name=LinerNotes-LP>{{cite AV media notes |title=French Gigs |others=[[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]] |year=1983 |last=AAA |type=LP liner notes}}</ref>\n*<ref name=LinerNotes-CD>{{cite AV media notes |title=French Gigs |others=[[Lol Coxhill]] and [[Fred Frith]] |year=1991 |last=AYAA |type=CD liner notes}}</ref>\n*<ref name=Scott>{{cite magazine |last=Scott |first=Richard |date=June 1993 |title=Lol Coxhill et Fred Frith: ''French Gigs'' |magazine=[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]] |publisher= |publication-place= |issue=112 |pages=56-57 |url