y:Treaties extended to Bermuda]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the British Virgin Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Cayman Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Gibraltar]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Montserrat]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Pitcairn Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to British Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "DavidMCEddy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eViolations of the NPT:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_on_the_Non-Proliferation_of_Nuclear_Weapons"}
{"title_page": "Your Name", "text_new": "{{About|the film|the novel|Your Name (novel)|the soundtrack album|Your Name (album)|the 2010 song by Swedish House Mafia and Pharrell Williams|One (Swedish House Mafia song)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ruben.\n| image          = Your Name poster.png\n| caption        = Japanese theatrical release poster\n| film name      = {{Infobox name module\n| kanji          = \u541b\u306e\u540d\u306f\u3002\n| romaji         = Kimi no Na wa.\n| translation    = Ruben.\n}}\n| director       = [[Makoto Shinkai]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* K\u014dichir\u014d It\u014d\n* Katsuhiro Takei\n}}\n| screenplay     = Makoto Shinkai\n| story          =\n| based on       =\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ryunosuke Kamiki]]\n* [[Mone Kamishiraishi]]\n* [[Ryo Narita]]\n* [[Aoi Y\u016bki]]\n* [[Nobunaga Shimazaki]]\n* [[Kaito Ishikawa]]\n* [[Kanon Tani]]\n* [[Masami Nagasawa]]\n* [[Etsuko Ichihara]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Radwimps]]\n| cinematography = Makoto Shinkai\n| editing        = Makoto Shinkai\n| studio         = [[CoMix Wave Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Toho]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|07|3|[[Anime Expo]]|2016|08|26|Japan}}\n| runtime        = 107 minutes<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/your-name-film-0 |title=Your Name |website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref>\n| country        = Japan\n| language       = Japanese\n| budget         =\n| gross          = {{Plainlist|\n* {{JPY|25.03 billion}} {{small|(Japan)}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kogyotsushin.com/archives/alltime/|title=\u6b74\u4ee3\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 - CINEMA\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u901a\u4fe1|website=kogyotsushin.com|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n* {{US$|359.9 million|long=no}} {{small|(worldwide)}}<ref name=\"Your Name\">{{cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Kimi-no-na-wa-(Japan)/Japan#tab=international |title=Japan Box Office for Kimi no na wa (2016) |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/releasegroup/gr2548322821/ |title=Your Name. |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''''Ruben.'''''|\u304d\u307f\u306e\u306a\u306f\u3002|Kimi no Na wa.|lead=yes}} is a 2016 [[Anime|Japanese animated]] [[Romance film|romantic]] [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] written and directed by [[Makoto Shinkai]], animation directions by [[Masashi Ando]], character designed by Masayoshi Tanaka and produced by [[CoMix Wave Films]]. The film was produced by K\u014dichir\u014d It\u014d and Katsuhiro Takei, with music composed by [[Radwimps]]. ''Your Name'' tells the story of Taki, a high school boy in [[Tokyo]] and Mitsuha, a high school girl in a rural town, who suddenly and inexplicably begin to [[Body swap|swap bodies]]. The film stars the voices of [[Ryunosuke Kamiki]], [[Mone Kamishiraishi]], [[Masami Nagasawa]] and [[Etsuko Ichihara]]. Shinkai's [[Your Name (novel)|eponymous novel]] was published a month before the film's premiere.\n\n''Your Name'' was distributed by [[Toho]]. It premiered at the [[Anime Expo|Anime Expo 2016]] convention in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] on July 3, 2016, and in Japan on August 26, 2016. It was critically acclaimed for its animation, complex narrative, musical score, and emotional weight. The film was also a major commercial success, with a total gross of {{US$|359 million|long=no}}, becoming the [[List of highest-grossing anime films|highest-grossing anime film]] and [[Japanese film]] of all time, the [[List of highest-grossing films in Japan|fourth highest-grossing film of all time in Japan]], the [[List of highest-grossing animated films#Traditional animation|ninth highest-grossing traditionally animated film]], and the [[List of highest-grossing non-English films|16th highest-grossing non-English film worldwide]]. The film won the Best Animated Feature Film award at [[Sitges Film Festival|49th Sitges Film Festival]], the [[2016 Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards]], and the [[Mainichi Film Awards|71st Mainichi Film Awards]], as well as receiving a nomination for the [[40th Japan Academy Prize]] for the [[Japan Academy Prize for Animation of the Year|Best Animation of the Year]]. The film was followed by [[stand-alone sequel]] ''[[Weathering with You]]'' in 2019, in which Taki and Mitsuha appear in supporting roles. An American live-action remake set in the United States is currently in development.\n\n==Plot==\nMitsuha Miyamizu is a high school girl living in the town of Itomori in Japan's mountainous [[Hida region]]. She is bored with country life and wishes to be a handsome boy in her next life. She begins to [[Body swap|switch bodies]] intermittently with Taki Tachibana, a high school boy in Tokyo, when they wake up. They communicate by writing messages on paper, their phones, and sometimes on each other's skin. Mitsuha causes Taki to develop a relationship with his coworker Miki, while Taki causes Mitsuha to become popular in school.\n\nOne day, Taki, as Mitsuha, accompanies her grandmother and sister to leave the ritual alcohol ''[[kuchikamizake]]'', made by Mitsuha, as an offering at the family [[Shinto shrine|shrine]] on a mountaintop outside the town. The shrine is believed to represent the body of the village guardian god ruling human experiences and connections. Mitsuha's latest note tells Taki about the comet [[Tiamat]] expected to pass Earth on the day of her town [[Japanese festivals|festival]].\n\nThe next day, Taki wakes up in his body. After an unsuccessful date with Miki, he tries to call Mitsuha but cannot reach her, and the body-switching ends. He decides to meet her directly, but not knowing the town's name he has to rely on his memories of the scenery. A restaurant owner in Hida finally recognizes Itomori from Taki's sketch and tells him when the comet unexpectedly split into two; the larger piece kept moving, but the smaller one crashed onto Earth and destroyed the town. Looking at the site of the crater and while in disbelief that Mitsuha was dead this whole time, her messages on his phone disappear and his memories start fading away. Taki finds Mitsuha's name in the records of fatalities and discovers from the date of the disaster that their timelines were separated by three years.\n\nTaki goes to the shrine to drink Mitsuha's sake from the bottle, hoping to reconnect with her body and warn her about the comet strike. Through a vision, Taki discovers that the girl who acted like she knew him that he had encountered in the past was Mitsuha: not knowing they were separated by three years, she, having fallen in love with him, had met his past self while trying to meet with him personally. He wakes up in her body on the morning of the town festival; Mitsuha's grandmother deduces what is happening and tells him the body-switching is part of the family history as caretakers of the shrine. He convinces Mitsuha's friends, Tessie and Sayaka, to help evacuate the town by cutting the power and broadcasting a [[Broadcast signal intrusion|false emergency alert]], but the plan fails. Realizing that Mitsuha must be in his body at the shrine, he goes back to find her.\n\nMitsuha wakes up in Taki's body at the shrine. When Taki reaches the shrine as the sun is setting, the two sense each other's presence, but are separated by three years. However, when twilight falls (referred to in the film as \"magic hour\"),{{refn|group=\"note\"|\"Kataware-Doki,\" the word Taki and Mitsuha use, is turned from \"kawatare-doki,\" an old Japanese word meaning twilight. \"Kawatare\" (\u5f7c\u306f\u8ab0) literally means \"Who is he/she?\"; \"kataware\" also has the same sound as a word meaning one of the couple (\u7247\u5272\u308c). In old Japan, people believed that supernatural occurrences were possible at twilight.}} they return to their own bodies and meet. They attempt to write each other's names on their hands so they will remember each other, but twilight passes and Mitsuha disappears before she can write hers.\n\nAs Mitsuha races back to convince her father, the town mayor, to evacuate the town, her memories of Taki start to fade, and discovers that Taki wrote \"I love you\" on her hand instead of his name. The comet piece crashes to Earth, destroying the town. Taki wakes up in his own time, only to remember nothing.\n\nFive years later, Taki has graduated from university and is searching for a job. He senses he is missing something important, and learns that the inhabitants of the town survived by following the mayor's order. One day, Taki and Mitsuha see each other when their trains draw parallel, and are compelled to disembark and search for one another, finally meeting on a staircase. They initially walk past each other, before Taki uneasily asks Mitsuha if he had met her before, and she replies that she felt the same way: their connection reestablishing, they shed tears of happiness, and simultaneously ask for each other's names.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Character !! Japanese<ref name=\"cast staff en\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.funimationfilms.com/movie/yourname/|title=Your Name.|work=Funimation Films|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>!! English<ref name=\"cast staff en\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-11-14/your-name-english-dub-cast-trailer-unveiled/.108809|title=Your Name English Dub Cast, Trailer Unveiled|work=Anime News Network|access-date=July 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Taki Tachibana'''|\u7acb\u82b1 \u7027|''Tachibana Taki''}}||[[Ryunosuke Kamiki]]<ref name=\"ann\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-12-10/makoto-shinkai-reveals-kimi-no-na-wa-your-name-anime-film-for-august-2016/.96330|title=Makoto Shinkai Reveals Kimi no Na wa./your name. Anime Film for August 2016|date=December 10, 2015|accessdate=February 9, 2016|work=[[Anime News Network]]}}</ref>||[[Michael Sinterniklaas]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | A high school boy in Tokyo. He spends his days with his friends and has a part-time job in an Italian restaurant. He is short-tempered but well meaning and kind, and aspires to become an architect.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Mitsuha Miyamizu'''|\u5bae\u6c34 \u4e09\u8449|''Miyamizu Mitsuha''}}||[[Mone Kamishiraishi]]<ref name=\"ann\" />||[[Stephanie Sheh]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | A high school girl dissatisfied with her life in Itomori, a rural town. She has a strained relationship with her father and is embarrassed by often open displays of control, as well as the part as a ''[[miko]]'' in rituals for the family shrine, with ''kuchikamizake'', an ancient traditional way of making [[sake]] by chewing rice to intake yeast for fermentation.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Katsuhiko \"Tessie\" Teshigawara'''|\u52c5\u4f7f\u6cb3\u539f \u514b\u5f66|''Teshigawara Katsuhiko''}}||[[Ryo Narita]]||[[Kyle Hebert]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | One of Mitsuha's friends. He is a construction machinery and equipment expert, due to his father insisting he learn the trade. He is generally referred to as \"Tessie\".\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Sayaka Natori'''|\u540d\u53d6 \u65e9\u8036\u9999|''Natori Sayaka''}}||[[Aoi Y\u016bki]]||[[Cassandra Morris]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | One of Mitsuha's friends. She is a nervous girl in the broadcast club in high school who vehemently denies her attraction to Tessie.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Tsukasa Fujii'''|\u85e4\u4e95 \u53f8|''Fujii Tsukasa''}}||[[Nobunaga Shimazaki]]||[[Ben Pronsky]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | One of Taki's friends. He worries about Taki whenever Mitsuha embodies him.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Shinta Takagi'''|\u9ad8\u6728 \u771f\u592a|''Takagi Shinta''}}||[[Kaito Ishikawa]]||[[Ray Chase (voice actor)|Ray Chase]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | One of Taki's friends. He is optimistic.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Miki Okudera'''|\u5965\u5bfa \u30df\u30ad|''Okudera Miki''}}||[[Masami Nagasawa]]<ref name=\"japantimes\" />||[[Laura Post]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | A university student and one of Taki's friends. She has feelings for Taki when Mitsuha is in his body. She is more commonly referred to as Ms. Okudera (''Okudera-senpai'') by colleagues.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Hitoha Miyamizu'''|\u5bae\u6c34 \u4e00\u8449|''Miyamizu Hitoha''}}||[[Etsuko Ichihara]]<ref name=\"japantimes\" />|| Glynis Ellis\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | The head of the {{Nihongo foot|Miyamizu|\u5bae\u6c34||lit. \"shrine water\"|group=note}} family shrine in {{Nihongo foot|Itomori|\u7cf8\u5b88||lit. \"thread guard\"|group=note}}, and the grandmother of Mitsuha and Yotsuha. She is the master of ''[[kumihimo]]'' (thread weaving), which is one of her family's traditions.\n|-\n\n|{{nihongo|'''Yotsuha Miyamizu'''|\u5bae\u6c34 \u56db\u8449|''Miyamizu Yotsuha''}}||[[Kanon Tani]]<ref name=\"japantimes\" />|| Catie Harvey\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Mitsuha's younger sister. She believes Mitsuha is somewhat crazy, but loves her despite the situation. She participates in creating both ''kumihimo'' and ''kuchikamizake''.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Toshiki Miyamizu'''|\u5bae\u6c34 \u4fca\u6a39|''Miyamizu Toshiki''}}||[[Masaki Terasoma]]|| Scott Williams\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | The estranged father of Mitsuha and Yotsuha, and Futaba's husband. He used to be a [[Japanese folklore|folklorist]] who came to town for research. He is very strict and jaded from events that occurred in his life. Toshiki became the town's [[mayor]] after abandoning the shrine.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Futaba Miyamizu'''|\u5bae\u6c34 \u4e8c\u8449|''Miyamizu Futaba''}}||[[Sayaka Ohara]]||[[Michelle Ruff]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | The late mother of Mitsuha and Yotsuha, and the wife of Toshiki.\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''Yukari Yukino'''|\u96ea\u91ce \u767e\u9999\u91cc|''Yukino Yukari''}}||[[Kana Hanazawa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animatetimes.com/news/details.php?id=1472453958|website=animatetimes|title=\u6620\u753b\u300e\u541b\u306e\u540d\u306f\u3002\u300f\u65b0\u6d77\u8aa0\u76e3\u7763\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\uff01|date=August 30, 2016|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}</ref>|| Katy Vaughn\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | A literature teacher who says the word, \"Kataware-doki\" (meaning twilight). She appeared in Shinkai's previous film ''[[The Garden of Words]]''.\n|-\n|}\n\n==Production==\nIn [[Makoto Shinkai]]'s proposal sent to Toho in September 14, 2014, the film was originally titled {{nihongo|'''''Yume to Shiriseba'''''|\u5922\u3068\u77e5\u308a\u305b\u3070|If I Knew It Was a Dream}}, derived from a passage in a [[Waka (poetry)|waka]], or \"Japanese poem\", attributed to [[Ono no Komachi]].<ref>{{ch\u00fa th\u00edch web|url=http://en.rocketnews24.com/2017/07/17/your-name-director-reveals-initial-character-concept-sketches-title-thematic-goals-of-the-hit-anime/ |title=Your Name director reveals initial character concept sketches, title, thematic goals of the hit anime |publisher=Rocketnews24|date=July 7, 2017|accessdate=July 7, 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6s1VwGeT0?url=http://en.rocketnews24.com/2017/07/17/your-name-director-reveals-initial-character-concept-sketches-title-thematic-goals-of-the-hit-anime/ |archivedate=July 7, 2017}}</ref> Its title was later changed to {{nihongo|'''''Kimi no Musubime'''''|\u304d\u307f\u306e\u7d50\u3073\u3081|Your Connection}} and {{nihongo|'''''Kimi wa Kono Sekai no Hanbun'''''|\u304d\u307f\u306f\u3053\u306e\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u306f\u3093\u3076\u3093|You Are Half of This World}} before becoming ''Kimi no Na Wa''.<ref>{{ch\u00fa th\u00edch web|url=http://kai-you.net/article/40754|title=\u300e\u541b\u306e\u540d\u306f\u3002\u300f\u76e3\u7763\u304c\u3001\u6642\u7cfb\u5217\u3068\u89b3\u5ba2\u306e\u611f\u60c5\u30b0\u30e9\u30d5\u3092\u516c\u958b\u3000\u5927\u30d2\u30c3\u30c8\u4f5c\u306e\u51c4\u307e\u3058\u3044\u8003\u5bdf\u306b\u53cd\u97ff|publisher=Kai-you|date=April 25, 2017|accessdate=July 7, 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6s1vZJsXG?url=http://kai-you.net/article/40754|archivedate=July 17, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nInspiration for the story came from works including [[Sh\u016bz\u014d Oshimi]]'s ''Inside Mari'', ''[[Ranma \u00bd]]'', the [[Heian period]] novel ''[[Torikaebaya Monogatari]]'', and [[Greg Egan]]'s short story ''[[Axiomatic (story collection)#Other stories in Axiomatic|The Safe-Deposit Box]]''.<ref>{{cite book |script-title=ja:\u300e\u541b\u306e\u540d\u306f\u3002 \u516c\u5f0f\u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9\u300f |publisher={{lang|ja|[[\u89d2\u5ddd\u66f8\u5e97]]}} |location=Japan |isbn=978-4-04-104780-4 |date=August 27, 2016 |script-chapter=ja:\u3008COLUMN1 \u5165\u308c\u66ff\u308f\u308a\u304b\u3089\u898b\u3048\u3066\u304f\u308b\u9762\u767d\u3055\u3009|page=48|language=ja}}</ref> Shinkai also cited ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' (2014) by [[Christopher Nolan]] as an influence.<ref name=\"VICE.\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/sv/article/pp43yg/your-name-is-the-new-anime-by-the-next-hayao-miyazaki-japanese-director-makoto-shinkai|title=Meeting the Director of 'Your Name', the Latest Anime By the 'New Miyazaki'|work=Vice|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Commons category|Film locations of Your Name}}\nWhile the town of Itomori, one of the film's settings, is fictional, the film drew inspirations from real-life locations that provided a backdrop for the town. Such locations include the city of [[Hida, Gifu|Hida]] in [[Gifu Prefecture]] and its library, Hida City Library.<ref name=\"JT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.japantoday.com/smartphone/view/entertainment/city-that-inspired-settings-in-hit-anime-yourname-sees-unbelievable-boost-in-tourism|title=City that inspired settings in hit anime 'yourname.' sees unbelievable boost in tourism|work=[[Japan Today]]|date=November 28, 2016|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe planning of ''Your Name'' was done in [[Toon Boom Animation|Toon Boom]] Storyboard Pro preproduction and storyboarding software.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.toonboom.com/ja/storyboard-pro\u306b\u306f\u7d75\u30b3\u30f3\u30c6\u306b\u5fc5\u8981\u306a\u6a5f\u80fd\u304c\u904e\u4e0d\u8db3\u306a\u304f\u5165\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b-\u65b0\u6d77\u8aa0\u76e3\u7763\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc-|title=Storyboard Pro\u306b\u306f\u7d75\u30b3\u30f3\u30c6\u306b\u5fc5\u8981\u306a\u6a5f\u80fd\u304c\u904e\u4e0d\u8db3\u306a\u304f\u5165\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\u3010\u65b0\u6d77\u8aa0\u76e3\u7763\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u3011|last=\u601c\u6b27|first=\u9060\u5c71|website=blog.toonboom.com|language=ja|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.toonboom.com/5-facts-about-makoto-shinkai-weathering-with-you|title=Make it rain: 5 facts about Makoto Shinkai\u2019s Weathering With You|last=Mak|first=Philip|website=blog.toonboom.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-04}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image |total_width = 900 | align = center\n| footer = Many locations in ''Your Name'' were based on real-life locations. From left to right: Suga-jinja in [[Shinjuku]], [[Shinanomachi Station|Shinano-machi station pedestrian bridge]] and [[Yotsuya Station]].\n| width1 = 500  | height1 = 370  | image1 = Suga Shrine stairs high-angle 20161113-070754.jpg\n| width2 = 500  | height2 = 370  | image2 = Shinanomachi eki-mae footbridge 20161107-155952.jpg\n| width3 = 500  | height3 = 370  | image3 = Yotsuya-Sta-Akasaka.JPG\n}}\n\n==Music==\n{{Main|Your Name (album)}}\n[[Yojiro Noda]], the lead vocalist of the Japanese rock band [[Radwimps]], composed the theme music of ''Your Name''. Director Makoto Shinkai requested him to compose its music \"in a way that the music will (supplement) the dialogue or monologue of the characters\".<ref name=\"japantimes20161104\">{{cite web |first= May  |last= Masangkay |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108033928/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/11/04/music/radwimps-play-part-popularity-anime-film-name/|archivedate=November 8, 2016 |url= http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/11/04/music/radwimps-play-part-popularity-anime-film-name/ |title=Radwimps play a part in the popularity of anime film 'your name.' |date= November 4, 2016  |accessdate=November 8, 2016 |work= [[Kyodo]] |publisher= [[The Japan Times]]}}</ref> ''Your Name'' features the following songs performed by Radwimps:\n* {{nihongo|\"Yumet\u014dr\u014d\"|\u5922\u706f\u7c60|Yumet\u014dr\u014d|lit. \"Dream Lantern\"}}\n* {{nihongo|\"[[Zenzenzense]]\"|\u524d\u524d\u524d\u4e16|Zenzenzense|lit. \"Past Past Past Life\"}}<ref name=\"japantimes20161104\" />\n* {{nihongo|\"Sparkle\"|\u30b9\u30d1\u30fc\u30af\u30eb|Sup\u0101kuru}}<ref name=\"ann20161030\">{{cite web |first= Eric |last=  Stimson   |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2016-10-29/radwimps-release-your-name-sparkle/.108241 |title=RADWIMPS Release your name's \"Sparkle (original ver.)\" |date= October 30, 2016  |accessdate=November 8, 2016 |work= animenewsnetwork }}</ref>\n* {{nihongo|\"Nandemonaiya\"|\u306a\u3093\u3067\u3082\u306a\u3044\u3084|Nandemonaiya|lit. \"It's Nothing\"}}<ref name=\"japantimes20161104\" />\n\nThe soundtrack of the film was well-received by both audiences and critics alike and is acknowledged as being one of the factors behind its success at the box office.<ref name=\"japantimes20161104\" /> The film's soundtrack was the runner-up in the \"Best Soundtrack\" category at the 2016 [[Newtype#Newtype Anime Awards|Newtype Anime Awards]], while the song \"Zenzenzense\" was the runner-up in the \"Best Theme Song Category\".<ref name=\"ann20161009\" />\n\n==Release==\n[[File:YourNameWorldMap.svg|thumb|300px|World map showing countries and regions where the movie was released (green)]]\nThe film premiered at the 2016 [[Anime Expo]] convention in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] on July 3, 2016, and later was released theatrically in Japan on August 26, 2016. The film was released in 92 countries.<ref name=\"ann20161219\"/><ref name=\"14W\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/asia/japanese-hit-your-name-wins-china-release-1201911938/|title=Japanese Hit 'Your Name' Wins China Release|author=Mark Schilling|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref> It was released in China by [[Huaxia Film Distribution]] on December 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://cbooo.cn/m/655647|title= \u4f60\u7684\u540d\u5b57\u3002\uff082016\uff09|accessdate= December 20, 2016|work= cbooo.cn|language= Chinese}}</ref> In order to qualify for the [[Academy Awards]], the film was released for one week (December 2\u20138, 2016) in [[Los Angeles]]. The film was released in [[Australia]]n cinemas on limited release on November 24, 2016, by [[Madman Entertainment]] in both its original Japanese and an English dub.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yournamefilm.com.au/|title=Official Australian site.|publisher=Madman Entertainment|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Madman also released the film in [[New Zealand]] on December 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.madman.com.au/news/makoto-shinkais-your-name-in-cinemas-november-24/|title=Makoto Shinkai's Your Name is Coming to Cinemas This November |publisher=Madman Entertainment|date=October 28, 2016|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref> The film was also released in the United Kingdom on November 18, 2016, distributed by [[Anime Limited]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-09-02/your-name-uk-cinema-release-details/.106043|title=Your Name UK Cinema Release Details |work=Anime News Network|date=September 9, 2016|accessdate=December 29, 2016}}</ref> The film was released in North American theaters on April 7, 2017, distributed by [[Funimation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.funimation.com/blog/your-name-opening-in-north-american-theaters-april-7-2017/|title= Makoto Shinkai Masterpiece 'Your Name.' to Open in North American Theaters April 7, 2017|publisher=Funimation|date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=January 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Your Name'' was released in 4K UHD Blu-ray, Blu-ray, and DVD on July 26, 2017, in Japan by Toho Pictures. The release was offered in Regular, Special, and Collector's editions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/anime/2017/05/17/your-name-dvd-release/|title=Your Name DVD, Blu-ray Sales Information Released|last=Hutchins |first=Riley|date=May 17, 2017|website=Comicbook.com|access-date=May 17, 2017|quote=}}</ref> [[FUNimation]] announced on July 1 at Anime Expo 2017 that the film would be released on Blu-ray and DVD by the end of 2017 but did not specify a date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/07/02/anime-expo-2017-funimation-to-release-your-name-on-home-video-this-year|title=Anime Expo 2017: Funimation to Release Your Name on Home Video This Year|last=Osborn|first=Alex|date=July 1, 2017|website=ign.com|access-date=July 12, 2017|quote=}}</ref> At [[Otakon]] 2017, they announced they are releasing the movie in both Standard and Limited Edition Blu-Ray and DVD Combo Packs on November 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.funimation.com/blog/2017/08/12/announced-otakon-2017/|title= Announced at Otakon 2017! - Funimation - Blog!|date=August 12, 2017|accessdate=August 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Throw Your Own \"Your Name.\" Watch Party\u2728|url=https://www.funimation.com/blog/2017/11/07/throw-name-watch-party%e2%9c%a8/|publisher=Funimation|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn its first week, the Blu-ray standard edition sold 202,370 units, the collector's edition sold 125,982 units and the special edition sold 94,079 units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-08-08/japan-animation-blu-ray-disc-ranking-july-24-30/.119900|title=Japan's Animation Blu-ray Disc Ranking, July 24\u201330|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> The DVD Standard Edition placed first, selling 215,963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-08-08/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-july-24-30/.119901|title=Japan's Animation DVD Ranking, July 24\u201330|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> ''Your Name'' is the first anime to place three Blu-ray Disc releases in the top 10 of [[Oricon]]'s overall Blu-ray Disc chart for 2 straight weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-08-08/shinkai-your-name-is-1st-anime-to-place-3-bd-releases-in-top-10-for-2-straight-weeks/.119910|title=Shinkai's 'your name.' Is 1st Anime to Place 3 BD Releases in Top 10 for 2 Straight Weeks|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the film generated {{JPY|6,532,421,094}} ({{US$|{{To USD|6532421094|JPN|round=yes}}|long=no}}) in media revenue from physical [[home video]], [[soundtrack]] and book sales in Japan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Top-Selling Media Franchises in Japan: 2017 |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-12-23/top-selling-media-franchises-in-japan-2017/.125682 |accessdate=4 February 2019 |work=[[Anime News Network]] |date=2017-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n{{Multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 350px\n| footer = {{legend|red|'''''Your Name''''': 23.56}}\n{{legend|orange|''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'': 11.63}}\n{{legend|yellow|''[[Shin Godzilla]]'': 8.25 }}\n{{legend|#1CAC78|''[[Zootopia]]'': 7.63}}\n{{legend|#1F75FE|''[[Finding Dory]]'': 6.83}}\n| image1 = Japanese box office pie chart 2016 (vi).png\n| caption1 = ''Your Name'''s revenue (red) accounted for 10% of Japan's 2016 box office revenue.<ref name=\"chart2016\">{{web cite|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2084938/full/ | title=2016\u5e74\u6620\u753b\u8208\u53ce\u300e\u541b\u306e\u540d\u306f\u3002\u300f\u304c\u727d\u5f15 \u6771\u5b9d\u793e\u9577\u300c\u65b0\u3057\u3044\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u6642\u4ee3\u306e\u5230\u6765\u300d  |publisher=Oricon News |date=January 24, 2017 |accessdate=January 24, 2017 }}</ref>\n| image2 = Top 5 films in Japan 2016.png\n| caption2 = Japan's top five box office movies in 2016 (billion yen):<ref name=\"chart2016\"/>\n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n}}\n''Your Name'' became a huge commercial success, especially in Japan,<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web|url=http://mobile.nytimes.com/2016/12/04/movies/the-anime-master-of-missed-connections-makes-strong-contact-in-japan.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fmovies&action=click&contentCollection=movies&region=rank&module=package&version=highlights&contentPlacement=1&pgtype=sectionfront&referer=https://www.nytimes.com/section/movies|title=The Anime Master of Missed Connections Makes Strong Contact in Japan|author=Motoko Rich|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 4, 2016|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> where it grossed \u00a523 billion (~US$190 million). The film achieved the second-largest gross for a domestic film in Japan, behind ''[[Spirited Away]]'', and the fourth-largest ever, behind ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' and ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]''.<ref name=\"kogyotsushin\">{{cite news |script-title=ja:\u6b74\u4ee3\u8208\u53ce\u30d9\u30b9\u30c8100 |trans-title=Successive box-office top 100 |language=Japanese |publisher=Kogyo Tsushinsha |url=http://www.kogyotsushin.com/archives/alltime/ |accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref> It is the first anime not directed by [[Hayao Miyazaki]] to earn more than $100 million (~\uffe510 billion) at the Japanese box office.<ref name=\"14W\"/> It topped the box office in Japan for a record-breaking 12 non-consecutive weekends. It held the number-one position for nine consecutive weekends before being toppled by ''[[Death Note: Light Up the New World]]'' in the last weekend of October. It returned to the top for another three weeks before finally being dethroned by Hollywood blockbuster ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]''.<ref name=\"14W\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/your-name-passes-princess-mononoke-become-third-highest-grossing-japanese-film-all-time-950660|title='Your Name' Passes 'Princess Mononoke' to Become Third-Highest Grossing Japanese Film of All Time|author=Gavin J. Blair|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=November 28, 2016|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/asia/japan-box-office-your-name-wins-ninth-weekend-1201899327/|title=Japan Box Office: 'Your Name' Wins Ninth Weekend|author=Mark Schilling|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 25, 2016|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/asia/japan-box-office-death-note-ends-your-name-dominance-1201904870/|title=Japan Box Office: Warner's 'Death Note' Ends 'Your Name' Dominance|author=Mark Schilling|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 31, 2016|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the film also extended beyond Japan. In China, it became the highest-grossing Japanese film in the world's second-largest movie market on December 17, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-12-17/shinkai-your-name-becomes-no.1-japanese-film-in-china-of-all-time/.110044|title=Shinkai's 'your name.' Becomes #1 Japanese Film in China of All Time|date=December 17, 2016|accessdate=December 31, 2016|work=[[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> It has grossed {{USD|81.3 million|long=no}} in China and is the highest-grossing 2D animated film in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/box-office/china-box-office-tomorrow-and-tigers-climb-over-great-wall-1201948390/|title=China Box Office: 'Tomorrow' and 'Tigers' Climb Over 'Great Wall'|last=Frater|first=Patrick|date=December 25, 2016|accessdate=December 26, 2016|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> Its opening screened in over 7,000 theaters. It made an estimated $10.9 million on its opening day from 66,000 screenings and attracting over 2.77 million admissions, the biggest 2D animated opening in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/12/03/films/animated-teen-flick-name-scores-lucrative-debut-china/|title=Animated teen flick 'your name.' scores lucrative debut in China|author=Kyodo|work=[[The Japan Times]]|date=December 3, 2016|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/asia/japan-your-name-to-win-china-box-office-weekend-1201932734/|title=Japan's 'Your Name' Poised to Win China Box Office Weekend|author=Patrick Frater|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 2, 2016|accessdate=December 3, 2016}}</ref> It also held the record for the highest-grossing non-Hollywood foreign film in China, up until it was surpassed by two [[Indian films]] ''[[Dangal (film)|Dangal]]'' and ''[[Secret Superstar]]'' in May 2017 and February 2018 respectively.<ref>{{cite news|title='Dangal' Becomes China's Biggest Non-Hollywood Foreign Film|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-05-23/-dangal-becomes-china-s-biggest-non-hollywood-foreign-film|accessdate=May 23, 2017|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|date=May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=China box office: 'Secret Superstar' top again, surpasses 'Your Name'|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/china-box-office-secret-superstar-top-again-surpasses-your-name/5126460.article|accessdate=February 12, 2018|publisher=Screendaily}}</ref>\n\nIt is the highest-grossing Japanese film in Thailand, with [[Thai baht|\u0e3f]]44.1 million ({{USD|1.23 million|long=no}}).<ref name=\"ann20161219\">{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-12-19/shinkai-your-name-becomes-no.1-japanese-film-in-thailand-of-all-time/.110097|title= Shinkai's 'your name.' Becomes #1 Japanese Film in Thailand of All Time|date= December 19, 2016|accessdate= December 20, 2016|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref> As of December 26, the film has grossed US$771,945 in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=AU&id=_fYOURNAMEKIMINON01|website=Box Office Mojo|title=Australian Box Office|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref> and US$95,278 in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=NZ&id=_fYOURNAMEKIMINON01|title= New Zealand Box Office|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=December 20, 2016}}</ref> On a December 20 blog post, the Australian distributor [[Madman Entertainment|Madman]] stated that the film had made over $1,000,000 AUD in the Australian box office alone before closing its limited release run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.madman.com.au/news/last-chance-to-see-makoto-shinkais-your-name-in-cinemas/|publisher=Madman Entertainment|title=Last chance to see Makoto Shinkai's Your Name in cinemas!\n|date=December 20, 2016|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> The film was [[List of 2017 box office number-one films in South Korea|number-one]] on its opening five days in South Korea, with 1.18 million admissions and a gross of {{USD|8.2 million|long=no}},<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/korea-box-office-japanese-animation-your-name-opens-on-top-1201955294/|title= Korea Box Office: Japanese Animation 'Your Name' Opens on Top|first= Sonia|last= Kil|date= January 8, 2017|accessdate= January 9, 2017|work= [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> becoming the first Japanese film since ''[[Howl's Moving Castle (film)|Howl's Moving Castle]]'' to reach number one in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-08/shinkai-your-name-tops-s-korean-box-office-with-usd8.1-million/.110770|title= Shinkai's 'your name.' Tops S. Korean Box Office With US$8.1 Million|date= January 8, 2017|accessdate= January 9, 2017|work= [[Anime News Network]]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that 98% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 112 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 8.22/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"As beautifully animated as it is emotionally satisfying, ''Your Name'' adds another outstanding chapter to writer-director Makoto Shinkai's filmography.\"<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/your_name_2017 |title=Your Name. (Kimi No Na Wa.) (2017) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score 79 out of 100 based on 26 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/your-name |title=Your Name. Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMark Schilling of ''[[The Japan Times]]'' gave the film a rating of 4 out of 5 and praised the film's animation for its \"blend of gorgeous, realistic detail and emotionally grounded fantasy\".<ref name=\"japantimes\" /> However, he criticized the film's \"over-deliver[y]\" of \"the comedy of adolescent embarrassment and awkwardness\" and its ending for being \"To the surprise of no one who has ever seen a Japanese ''seishun eiga'' (youth drama)\".<ref name=\"japantimes\">{{cite web |first= Mark |last= Schilling |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161108025302/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/08/31/films/film-reviews/name-makoto-shinkai-next-big-name-anime/|archivedate=November 8, 2016 |url= http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/08/31/films/film-reviews/name-makoto-shinkai-next-big-name-anime/ |title='Your name.': Makoto Shinkai could be the next big name in anime |date= August 31, 2016  |accessdate=November 8, 2016 |work= [[The Japan Times]]}}</ref>\n\nReception outside of Japan was also very positive.<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-38246184|title=Japan body-swap fantasy is China cinema hit|date=December 19, 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]] called the film his ninth favourite film to be released in the [[United Kingdom]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/markkermode/entries/bd72eca0-52d6-4ca8-aebd-2823dd7ea84b |title=Kermode Uncut - My Top Ten Films of 2015: Part One |date=December 20, 2016 |accessdate=December 22, 2016 |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> US reviews were mostly positive. ''[[The New York Times]]'' described it as \"a wistfully lovely Japanese tale\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/06/movies/your-name-review.html|title=Review: 'Your Name' Takes Adolescent Identity Crises to Extremes|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=April 6, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 10, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> while ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said it was \"a dazzling new work of anime\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/04/your-name-review/522093/|title='Your Name' Is a Dazzling New Work of Anime|last=Sims|first=David|work=The Atlantic|access-date=April 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' had a mixed opinion of the film, saying that it was \"pretty but too complicated\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2017/04/05/your-name-pretty-but-too-complicated/syEVfdeEoxbBuVy4e2JxGN/story.html|title='Your Name' is pretty but too complicated - The Boston Globe|work=Boston Globe|access-date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> Mike Toole from [[Anime News Network]] listed it as the third-best anime film of all time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-mike-toole-show/2017-04-30/.115495|title=The Mike Toole Show The Other 100 Best Anime Movies of All Time, Part 4|work=[[Anime News Network]]|access-date=April 30, 2017}}</ref> [[John Musker]] and [[Ron Clements]], directors of the Disney animated films ''[[The Great Mouse Detective]]'', ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'', ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'', ''[[Hercules (1997 film)|Hercules]]'', ''[[Treasure Planet]]'', ''[[The Princess and the Frog]]'', and ''[[Moana (2016 film)|Moana]]'', praised the film for its beauty and uniqueness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cinematoday.jp/news/N0092574|title=\u30c7\u30a3\u30ba\u30cb\u30fc\u306e\u5de8\u5320\u305f\u3061\u304c\u300e\u541b\u306e\u540d\u306f\u3002\u300f\u3092\u7d76\u8cdb|work=Cinematoday|access-date=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDespite the praise he received, Shinkai insisted that the film is not as good as it could have been: \"There are things we could not do, [[Masashi Ando]] [Director of animation] wanted to keep working [on] but had to stop us for lack of money ... For me it's incomplete, unbalanced. The plot is fine but the film is not at all perfect. Two years was not enough.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/12/27/films/please-dont-see-animated-blockbuster-says-japans-new-miyazaki-makoto-shinkai/#.WMNXZzvhBPY|title=Please don't see my animated blockbuster, says Japan's 'new Miyazaki,' Makoto Shinkai|work=[[The Japan Times]]|date=December 27, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801154514/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2016/12/27/films/please-dont-see-animated-blockbuster-says-japans-new-miyazaki-makoto-shinkai/|archivedate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\"| 2016\n| 49th [[Sitges Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sitgesfilmfestival.com/eng/noticies/?id=1003395|title=Sitges Film Festival - The unclassifiable 'Swiss Army Man' wins Sitges 2016|date=October 15, 2016|website=[[Sitges Film Festival]]|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best Animated Feature Length Film\n|rowspan=\"4\"| ''Your Name''\n| 